📁 2. Project Structure (Production-grade)

Use this folder setup:

/agent
   ├── AGENT_STATE.md        ← current progress
   ├── TASK_PLAN.md         ← full roadmap
   ├── DECISIONS.md         ← architecture decisions
   ├── CONTEXT.md           ← domain knowledge
   ├── state.json           ← machine-readable state
   └── prompts/
         ├── resume.txt
         ├── next_step.txt
         └── summarize.txt
🧩 3. Each File’s Responsibility
✅ AGENT_STATE.md (runtime memory)

Current step

Completed work

Next steps
👉 This is your checkpoint

✅ TASK_PLAN.md (long-term plan)

End-to-end architecture

Phases (Planner → KG → SQL → Eval)

✅ DECISIONS.md

Why DynamoDB over RDS

Why RAG used
👉 Prevents Copilot from “changing direction”

✅ CONTEXT.md

Business/domain info

Schema, APIs, constraints

✅ state.json

Used later if you:

Add scripts

Build real agents

⚙️ 4. Prompt System (This is the magic)

Create reusable prompts.

🔥 resume.txt
Writing

Read the following files carefully:

AGENT_STATE.md

TASK_PLAN.md

DECISIONS.md

Summarize current progress

Identify current step

Continue implementation from where it stopped

Do NOT restart or redesign

Follow constraints strictly

▶️ next_step.txt
Based on AGENT_STATE.md, implement the next step.
Update AGENT_STATE.md after completion.
🧠 summarize.txt
Summarize progress and update AGENT_STATE.md with:
- Completed
- Current step
- Next steps
🔁 5. Workflow (How you actually use it daily)
🟢 Step 1: Start work

Ask Copilot:

“Follow prompts/resume.txt”

🟡 Step 2: During work

After each task:

“Update AGENT_STATE.md”

🔴 Step 3: If VS Code closes/crashes

After reopening:

“Follow prompts/resume.txt”

👉 It reconstructs context from files

